to address issues of prejudice, repression, and exclusion. But the music is now a worldwide phenomenon, and outside the United States it has been taken up by those facing similar struggles. Flip the Script offers a close look at the role of hip hop in Europe, where it has become a politically powerful and commercially successful form of expression for the children and grandchildren of immigrants from former colonies. Through analysis of recorded music and other media, as well as interviews and fieldwork with hip hop communities, J. Griffith Rollefson shows how this music created by black Americans is deployed by Senegalese Parisians, Turkish Berliners, and South Asian Londoners to both differentiate themselves from and relate themselves to the dominant culture. By listening closely to the ways these postcolonial citizens in Europe express their solidarity with African Americans through music, Rollefson shows, we can literally hear the hybrid realities of a global double consciousness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aHip-hopzEurope, Western. 0aHip-hop-Europe, Western. 0aMusiczEurope, WesternxAfrican American influences. 0aMusic-Europe, Western-African American influences. 0aPostcolonialism and music. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aEurope.  ablack Atlantic.  aculture industry.  adouble consciousness.  aglobal hip hop.  aimmigration.  amusic.  apopular music.  apostcolonialism.  arace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226496351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226496351/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles